{"key":"post-12730820","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12730820</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;illmannered_1 said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Any &quot;new&quot; teks you can recommend that gives a definite amount to use?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There are no reputable 'teks' that give exact amounts of anything.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Manure is fungi food, vermiculite is fungi food, compost is fungi food, spent coffee grinds are fungi food, coir is fungi food, etc., etc.&amp;nbsp;  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gypsum is a supplement.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You really don't need gypsum at more than 5% to 10% by volume, which is about 3% to 5% by weight.&amp;nbsp; Adding too much isn't going to hurt anything, but isn't going to help either.&amp;nbsp; It would be like you taking too much of a calcium supplement.&amp;nbsp; Your body will use what it needs and excrete the excess.&amp;nbsp; The reason the early 'teks' don't mention gypsum is because it wasn't known at that time how valuable it is.&amp;nbsp; In addition, many people in the online world don't follow the advances in commercial mushroom farming.&amp;nbsp; When you have to sell your product for $3/pound, you have to get the most edge you can or go broke.&amp;nbsp; The lessons and research conducted by the mushroom farming industry are applicable to nearly any species of mushroom, especially edibles like &lt;i&gt;P cubensis&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To anyone who wants a 'recipe tek', simply make up your own and it's as valid as what I or anyone else will make.&amp;nbsp; Use coir, manure, verm, compost, etc., in any ratio you want or have available.&amp;nbsp; They're all good by themselves, but mixed together are even better.&amp;nbsp; When you're done, toss in a bit of granulated gypsum, bring it all to field capacity and pasteurize at 140F for an hour to 90 minutes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If it would help to see a simple bulk substrate being put together, check out the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Horse-Manure-Substrate&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;manure substrate video&lt;/a&gt; clip on my website.&amp;nbsp; It shows only horse manure and gypsum to keep it simple, but adding any other bulk substrate material to the mix makes it even better.&amp;nbsp; There's a good demonstration of getting 'field capacity' moisture content in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Casing-Layer-Preparation&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;casing layer video clip&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp; These are just sample clips cut from the full release on DVD, but they show enough to get the point.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12734032</next>\n<prev>12730799</prev>\n<first>12729833</first>\n<last>12734032</last>\n<when>1276359508</when>\n<utime>06/12/10 07:18 PM</utime>\n</post>"}